&gt; On 5/12/07, Mark Baker &lt;distobj@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; On 5/11/07, Eric J. Bowman &lt;eric@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;  &gt; Has Microsoft&#39;s &quot;Windows Live Contacts API&quot; confused PUT 
&gt; and POST?
&gt; &gt;  &gt;
&gt; &gt;  &gt; [1] http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb447763.aspx
&gt; &gt;  &gt; [2] http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb463980.aspx
&gt; &gt;  &gt;
&gt; &gt;  &gt; Specifically, isn&#39;t [1] a fine example of how not to use PUT?
&gt; 
&gt; [1] is wrong (I didn&#39;t bother looking at [2]). Let&#39;s make up 
&gt; a document format to illustrate. You send a GET and receive this in
&gt; response:
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;foo&gt;
&gt;    &lt;bar&gt;1&lt;/bar&gt;
&gt;    &lt;baz&gt;2&lt;/baz&gt;
&gt; &lt;/foo&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; so it seems that [1] says
&gt; 
&gt; PUT
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;foo&gt;
&gt;    &lt;bar&gt;1&lt;/bar&gt;
&gt; &lt;/foo&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; will leave &lt;baz&gt; with content of 2, rather than not present at all.
&gt; That&#39;s pretty short-sighted, because it places 
&gt; application-specific requirements on the server. If PUT meant 
&gt; PUT, then you could just drop Apache in and the client would 
&gt; be none the wiser.
